Pappus of Alexandria was a Greek mathematician who lived about 300 AD. His most important work is a mathematical treatise in eight books, of which the first and part of the second are lost. This was made known to modern scholars hy Commandinus. The work exerted a happy influence on the revival of geometry in the seventeenth century. Pappus was not himself a mathematician οἱ the first rank. but he preserved for the world many extracts or analyses of lost works, and by his commentaries added to their interest.
